1
00:00:38,363 --> 00:00:40,545
It's the early 1970s.

2
00:00:40,797 --> 00:00:42,964
And a force is sweeping through rock

3
00:00:43,064 --> 00:00:46,150
with a sound big enough
to fill football stadiums.

4
00:00:46,350 --> 00:00:48,890
Its name, Led Zeppelin.

5
00:00:49,204 --> 00:00:53,755
A group that will become the first
gladiators of Stadium Rock.

6
00:00:53,955 --> 00:00:57,010
# It's been a long time
since I rock-and-rolled

7
00:00:59,540 --> 00:01:02,498
# It's been a long time
since I did the Stroll

8
00:01:05,141 --> 00:01:08,941
# Ooh, let me get it back,
let me get it back, let me get it back

9
00:01:09,041 --> 00:01:11,290
# mm-baby, where I come from

10
00:01:11,490 --> 00:01:15,332
For the next 20 years,
stadium rock will be an elite club

11
00:01:15,432 --> 00:01:19,300
with only a handful of
ambitious bands can hope to join.

12
00:01:26,824 --> 00:01:28,931
Do you believe in rock 'n roll?

13
00:01:29,017 --> 00:01:32,452
For this groups,
size really does matter.

14
00:01:32,700 --> 00:01:36,597
It is arrogance
with a cock.

15
00:01:40,736 --> 00:01:45,571
These are performers who specialize
in driving audiences wild.

16
00:01:45,982 --> 00:01:48,870
It's the greatest job in the world!

17
00:01:53,007 --> 00:01:56,759
But they will discover through
a global stadium rock show

18
00:01:56,859 --> 00:02:00,176
that their music isn't just being
listened to around the world

19
00:02:00,276 --> 00:02:02,720
but might also help change it.

20
00:02:04,113 --> 00:02:05,564
We had the whole planet.

21
00:02:05,823 --> 00:02:09,443
And it turns out that
the 'lingua franca' of the world

22
00:02:09,543 --> 00:02:11,726
is not English,
it's rock 'n roll.

23
00:02:13,304 --> 00:02:16,587
This is the story
of the age of Stadium Rock.

24
00:02:17,543 --> 00:02:19,713
When a succession of great artists

25
00:02:19,813 --> 00:02:22,210
took the music
onto a global stage

26
00:02:22,310 --> 00:02:24,920
and played for the higher
stakes possible.

27
00:02:25,534 --> 00:02:28,593
You are sort of like
the Aztec Sun Prince.

28
00:02:28,628 --> 00:02:31,854
You're there in your palace
but you know

29
00:02:31,954 --> 00:02:33,848
when the year's up,
the priest is gonna come,

30
00:02:33,883 --> 00:02:37,198
drag you out, take you up the pyramid
and cut your heart out with a knife.

31
00:02:36,656 --> 00:02:41,615
# ...of the world.

32
00:02:54,052 --> 00:03:00,957
# There's a lady who's sure
all that glitters is gold

33
00:03:01,290 --> 00:03:06,849
# And she's buying a stairway to heaven

34
00:03:06,949 --> 00:03:10,163
Led Zeppelin came to America
at the end of the 60s,

35
00:03:10,263 --> 00:03:15,801
and by 1973 were playing to audiences
of over 50,000 people.

36
00:03:19,264 --> 00:03:23,304
On stage, singer Robert Plant,
combined power and intimacy

37
00:03:23,404 --> 00:03:27,181
to create a magical vibe
that defined stadium rock.

38
00:03:28,151 --> 00:03:33,725
# And she's buying
a stairway to heaven

39
00:03:33,834 --> 00:03:36,675
Great stadium rock is really
about the universal.

40
00:03:36,710 --> 00:03:40,655
It's about having those songs
that the whole world wants to sing.

41
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:44,819
Sometimes it lacks the subtlety
and refinement that gets critics excited

42
00:03:44,854 --> 00:03:49,334
and they tend to be quite
harsh about stadium rock,

43
00:03:49,369 --> 00:03:52,099
it's almost become
a term of abuse.

44
00:03:52,152 --> 00:03:57,006
And yet, the great stadium rock bands
take it beyond a big show,

45
00:03:57,206 --> 00:04:02,041
they take it into the realm
of spirit and substance.

46
00:04:02,716 --> 00:04:05,070
But I've got some good news.
Listen!

47
00:04:05,170 --> 00:04:10,914
# If there's a bustle in your hedgerow,
don't be alarmed now,

48
00:04:11,114 --> 00:04:15,428
# It's just a spring clean
for the May Queen

49
00:04:16,249 --> 00:04:22,237
I remember seeing Led Zeppelin
and it was really a religious experience.

50
00:04:22,337 --> 00:04:25,573
It was so perfect,

51
00:04:25,673 --> 00:04:29,362
and so much everything that I would
ever want to aspire to be.

52
00:04:31,526 --> 00:04:34,194
Backstage, Zeppelin's manager,
Peter Grunt,

53
00:04:34,294 --> 00:04:36,759
scourge of concert
promoters around the world,

54
00:04:36,859 --> 00:04:39,334
would be working
his own kind of magic.

55
00:04:39,603 --> 00:04:42,008
Don't fucking talk to me,
it's my bloody act!

56
00:04:42,108 --> 00:04:45,325
I think I'll leave you anytime. You
couldn't even give them a starting line.

57
00:04:45,425 --> 00:04:48,224
You are the fucking controller
of the thing, aren't you?

58
00:04:49,366 --> 00:04:53,012
For concert promoters, Grunt was
an intimidating and infamous figure.

59
00:04:53,212 --> 00:04:56,458
But he would have a lasting
impact on the business of rock.

60
00:04:57,692 --> 00:05:00,454
You rented it and you controlled it.

61
00:05:00,489 --> 00:05:03,217
Isn't selling fucking
pirate posters.

62
00:05:03,629 --> 00:05:07,088
Led Zeppelin were a monumentally
important band.

63
00:05:07,188 --> 00:05:08,594
They literally changed the economics.

64
00:05:08,694 --> 00:05:11,225
They said, we'll take 90%
and you'll keep 10%,

65
00:05:11,425 --> 00:05:13,050
to the promoters,
which was an inversion

66
00:05:13,085 --> 00:05:14,125
of the way it had always worked.

67
00:05:14,160 --> 00:05:16,196
And they had the nerve
and the toughness to do it.

68
00:05:16,296 --> 00:05:19,114
And they were such a powerful draw,
that having 10% of Led Zeppelin

69
00:05:19,214 --> 00:05:21,589
was still worth it to the promoters.

70
00:05:27,157 --> 00:05:30,031
The big bands of the era
followed Zeppelin's lead,

71
00:05:30,131 --> 00:05:32,202
both The Who and The Rolling Stones

72
00:05:32,302 --> 00:05:35,794
found the emphasis of their career
shifting from making records

73
00:05:35,894 --> 00:05:38,494
to filling the largest spaces possible.

74
00:05:41,112 --> 00:05:42,991
These were, as it were,
slightly old guard,

75
00:05:43,091 --> 00:05:47,404
these were people who had been
big towards the end of the 1960s.

76
00:05:47,504 --> 00:05:50,930
But they in turn inspired
new generations.

77
00:05:51,030 --> 00:05:53,509
# I see a little silhouette of a man

78
00:05:53,544 --> 00:05:57,113
# Scaramouch, scaramouch
will you do the fandango

79
00:05:57,148 --> 00:06:00,784
# Thunderbolt and lightning
