80
00:06:00,819 --> 00:06:06,918
# Gallileo, Gallileo, Gallileo, Gallileo,
Gallileo Figaro - magnifico

81
00:06:08,404 --> 00:06:13,220
1975 was the year the group Queen
emerged onto the world's stage.

82
00:06:13,420 --> 00:06:17,182
'Bohemian Rhapsody' brought comparisons
with the epics of Led Zeppelin.

83
00:06:17,530 --> 00:06:21,720
On tour in Japan, they were hailed
as visiting gods.

84
00:06:24,674 --> 00:06:28,453
We got on the plane, a young,
up-and-coming, hopeful group in England,

85
00:06:28,553 --> 00:06:31,860
and we got off the plane in Tokyo
like The Beatles.

86
00:06:31,960 --> 00:06:36,186
It was very...
blindingly strange.

87
00:06:38,763 --> 00:06:41,949
# Oh mama mia, mama mia,
mama mia let me go

88
00:06:42,049 --> 00:06:46,251
We're completely overwhelmed
by what's happened since we came here.

89
00:06:46,351 --> 00:06:48,693
It's never happened to us
in any other country.

90
00:06:59,586 --> 00:07:03,831
Most groups, at that point,
were very much against

91
00:07:03,931 --> 00:07:05,023
putting on any kind of show.

92
00:07:05,123 --> 00:07:07,129
It was very much like,
let's get into our music, man,

93
00:07:07,329 --> 00:07:09,551
and everything else
can take a back seat.

94
00:07:09,651 --> 00:07:12,389
We weren't like that.
We thought, "No. We entertain people."

95
00:07:12,901 --> 00:07:16,488
# A baby I was when you took my hand

96
00:07:16,717 --> 00:07:19,601
# And the light of
the night burned bright

97
00:07:20,419 --> 00:07:23,514
# And the people all
stared didn't understand

98
00:07:23,714 --> 00:07:26,953
# But you knew my name on sight

99
00:07:27,429 --> 00:07:30,839
Queen's live act was centered
around singer Freddy Mercury,

100
00:07:30,939 --> 00:07:34,291
one of the greatest frontmen
in the history of rock.

101
00:07:34,714 --> 00:07:37,935
People actually believed
when he first used to come on sort of...

102
00:07:38,135 --> 00:07:39,648
Hell thunderbolts!

103
00:07:44,619 --> 00:07:47,815
And we used to dress somebody up
as Freddy and just flash a light,

104
00:07:47,915 --> 00:07:49,364
and now I'm here,
now I'm there,

105
00:07:49,464 --> 00:07:51,532
and of course,
one of them was him.

106
00:07:55,661 --> 00:07:58,326
It seemed almost
like a magic show.

107
00:08:05,046 --> 00:08:07,669
The thing about it that
I loved mostly was that

108
00:08:07,722 --> 00:08:10,478
he wasn't asking your permission,
he simply was saying,

109
00:08:10,578 --> 00:08:12,843
this is who I am,
take it or leave it.

110
00:08:13,286 --> 00:08:15,583
That's what rock...
It's putting your chin out and say,

111
00:08:15,683 --> 00:08:17,634
"Go ahead, take your best shot."

112
00:08:23,120 --> 00:08:26,878
Queen's show always ended
with the audience demanding more.

113
00:08:26,968 --> 00:08:29,803
And it was this ritual
which inspired Brian May

114
00:08:29,903 --> 00:08:33,054
to write the most famous
stadium anthem of them all.

115
00:08:34,457 --> 00:08:37,391
There was a place called
Bingley Hall, near Birmingham,

116
00:08:37,491 --> 00:08:38,709
which we used to play,

117
00:08:38,809 --> 00:08:42,264
and one night it was packed
and heaving and sweaty.

118
00:08:42,364 --> 00:08:43,706
It was an amazing gig.

119
00:08:43,820 --> 00:08:46,668
And when we came off
they didn't stop singing.

120
00:08:46,768 --> 00:08:47,840
They were singing to us.

121
00:08:47,940 --> 00:08:49,665
They were singing
'You'll never walk alone'.

122
00:08:49,812 --> 00:08:51,719
And we all looked at
each other and thought,

123
00:08:51,819 --> 00:08:56,401
"Something is really happening here.
This is a complete interaction."

124
00:08:56,897 --> 00:08:59,552
And that night I woke up
in the middle of the night

125
00:08:59,752 --> 00:09:03,349
thinking, what would an audience do
if you gave them permission,

126
00:09:03,449 --> 00:09:04,622
what would they do.

127
00:09:06,774 --> 00:09:09,043
They could stand, they could clap,
they could sing something

128
00:09:09,078 --> 00:09:11,203
which made them feel they were
bonded together,

129
00:09:11,238 --> 00:09:13,051
something which made them
feel strong.

130
00:09:14,984 --> 00:09:17,791
# We will, we will rock you

131
00:09:17,826 --> 00:09:21,066
Come on! Sing it everybody!

132
00:09:21,101 --> 00:09:24,271
# We will, we will rock you

133
00:09:24,306 --> 00:09:28,278
I think it was very stripped down
bareness of it.

134
00:09:29,950 --> 00:09:32,478
It was just sort of
caught people.

135
00:09:34,478 --> 00:09:35,873
You know, "Rock!"

136
00:09:39,875 --> 00:09:41,233
When it was played live,

137
00:09:41,333 --> 00:09:44,716
'We will rock you' would segue
into a song of Freddy Mercury's,

138
00:09:44,816 --> 00:09:48,393
the equally bombastic,
'We are the Champions'.

139
00:09:49,880 --> 00:09:55,834
# We are the champions, my friend

140
00:09:57,081 --> 00:10:03,918
# And we'll keep on fighting
till the end

141
00:10:05,022 --> 00:10:08,359
The songs would provide
an explosive concert finale

142
00:10:08,459 --> 00:10:10,369
for the rest of Queen's career.

143
00:10:13,660 --> 00:10:17,086
'We will rock you' and
'We are the champions'

144
00:10:17,186 --> 00:10:20,683
are triumphalist rock songs.

145
00:10:22,884 --> 00:10:28,698
It is all about the communication,
the empathy, the energy exchange,

146
00:10:28,798 --> 00:10:32,101
between thousands of people
in a stadium

147
00:10:32,201 --> 00:10:35,819
and that larger-than-life
character on the stage.

148
00:10:35,919 --> 00:10:39,310
# We are the champions

149
00:10:40,824 --> 00:10:43,297
That is the essence of stadium rock.

150
00:10:43,397 --> 00:10:52,378
# No time for losers,
'cause we are the champions...

151
00:10:54,396 --> 00:10:57,476
# of the world.

152
00:11:18,504 --> 00:11:22,695
The sports arenas of the USA
were stadium rock spiritual home.

153
00:11:22,795 --> 00:11:25,512
And both 'We will rock you' and
'We are the champions'

154
00:11:25,612 --> 00:11:27,933
became an eternal part
of their culture.

155
00:11:30,909 --> 00:11:32,611
It was in the 1970s

156
00:11:32,711 --> 00:11:35,624
that American bands created
a brand of theatrical rock

157
00:11:35,724 --> 00:11:37,723
purpose-built for these venues.

158
00:11:38,278 --> 00:11:40,277
Kiss! Kiss! Kiss!

159
00:11:40,375 --> 00:11:45,844
American stadium rock is really
just rock as grand entertainment.

160
00:11:46,144 --> 00:11:50,002
In America you get
a tradition that gives you Aerosmith,

161
00:11:50,102 --> 00:11:52,865
and ultimately gives you Bon Jovi.

162
00:11:52,965 --> 00:11:54,245
Or it gives you Kiss.

163
00:11:54,536 --> 00:11:58,532
Just the theater of rock
without any substance.

164
00:12:00,603 --> 00:12:03,808
# You show us everything you've got

165
00:12:04,008 --> 00:12:07,186
# You keep on dancin
